12 AUTHORS: Add the following House Coauthors: West (Josh) and Munson
13 AMENDMENT NO. 1. Strike the stricken title, enacting clause, and
entire bill and insert:
14
15 "An Act relating to the Attorney General; defining
terms; establishing a certain pilot program under the
16 Office of the Attorney General; providing purpose;
listing qualifying expenses; stating eligibility
17 requirements; requiring certain application process
and review criteria; requiring certain reports and
18 compliance; authorizing the Office of the Attorney
General to take certain actions; requiring electronic
19 submissions of certain report; authorizing
promulgation of rules; amending Section 1, Chapter
20 376, O.S.L. 2023 (21 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 748.3),
which relates to the Victims of Human Trafficking and
21 Prevention Revolving Fund; expanding the scope of
allowable expenditures; providing for codification;
22 providing an effective date; and declaring an
emergency.
23
24
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 1379 Page 1

1 BE I T ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
2 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
3 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 18r-1 of Title 74, unless there
4 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
5 A. For the purposes of this act:
6 1. “Labor trafficking” means human trafficking for labor as
7 defined in Section 748 of Title 21 of the Oklahoma Statutes;
8 2. “Private organization” means a nonprofit corporation
9 certified by the Office of the Attorney General that provides
10 support services to adult victims of human trafficking;
11 3. “Sexual trafficking” means human trafficking for commercial
12 sex as defined in Section 748 of Title 21 of the Oklahoma Statutes;
13 and
14 4. “Victim” means a person against whom an act of labor
15 trafficking or sexual trafficking has been committed.
16 B. 1. The Office of the Attorney General shall establish a
17 two-year pilot program to support victims of sexual and labor
18 trafficking. The Office of the Attorney General shall make grants
19 available from funds in the Victims of Human Trafficking and
20 Prevention Revolving Fund pursuant to Section 748.3 of Title 21 of
21 the Oklahoma Statutes for the purposes of this act. The grants
22 shall be made directly to no more than ten private organizations in
23 this state.
24
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 1379 Page 2

1 2. The purpose of such grants shall be to reimburse private
2 organizations for the qualifying expenses of programs providing
3 services to victims of sexual and labor trafficking. Qualifying
4 expenses include, but are not limited to:
5 a. emergency shelter and transitional housing services,
6 b. mental health counseling and trauma-informed therapy,
7 c. medical and dental care services,
8 d. substance abuse treatment and recovery support,
9 e. legal assistance and advocacy services,
10 f. job training and employment assistance,
11 g. educational services and General Educational
12 Development (GED) completion assistance,
13 h. case management and coordination of services,
14 i. transportation assistance,
15 j. basic needs assistance including food, clothing, and
16 personal care items,
17 k. life skills training and financial literacy education,
18 l. child care services for victims with minor children,
19 and
20 m. other services deemed necessary by the Office of the
21 Attorney General for the recovery and restoration of
22 victims.
23
24
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 1379 Page 3

1 3. In order for a private organization to be considered
2 eligible to receive grants pursuant to the provisions of this
3 subsection, a private organization shall:
4 a. be in good standing and compliant with nonprofit
5 requirements of this state and federal law,
6 b. have demonstrated experience providing services to
7 victims of sexual or labor trafficking,
8 c. agree to provide services without regard to the
9 immigration status of the victim,
10 d. maintain confidentiality of victim information in
11 accordance with applicable state and federal law, and
12 e. maintain adequate liability insurance coverage as
13 determined by the Office of the Attorney General.
14 4. The Office of the Attorney General shall establish an
15 application process and review criteria for private organizations
16 seeking grants pursuant to the provisions of this subsection. The
17 Office of the Attorney General shall prioritize organizations that:
18 a. demonstrate a track record of successful service
19 delivery to victims,
20 b. employ trauma-informed care practices,
21 c. provide culturally competent services,
22 d. collaborate with law enforcement and other service
23 providers, and
24
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 1379 Page 4

1 e. serve geographic areas or populations with
2 demonstrated need.
3 5. Grants provided to private organizations pursuant to this
4 act shall be used solely for the provision of direct services to
5 victims and shall not be used for administrative overhead that
6 exceeds fifteen percent (15%) of the total grant amount.
7 C. Any private organization that receives a grant pursuant to
8 the provisions of this act shall submit quarterly reports to the
9 Office of the Attorney General that include the following
10 information:
11 1. Number of victims served;
12 2. Types of services provided to victims;
13 3. Expenditure of grant funds; and
14 4. Outcomes achieved to the extent measurable.
15 D. The Office of the Attorney General shall monitor compliance
16 of private organizations that receive grants pursuant to this act.
17 The Office of the Attorney General may:
18 1. Require periodic reports on services provided and outcomes
19 achieved;
20 2. Conduct site visits and review of grant recipients;
21 3. Review financial records and documentation of expenditures;
22 4. Require corrective action plans for organizations that do
23 not meet grant eligibility requirements; and
24
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 1379 Page 5

1 5. Suspend or terminate grants to private organizations that
2 fail to comply with the terms and conditions of the grant or the
3 requirements established pursuant to this act.
4 E. The Office of the Attorney General shall compile an annual
5 report regarding the implementation of the pilot program established
6 in this act. The report shall be submitted electronically to the
7 Governor, the President Pro Tempore of the Senate, and the Speaker
8 of the House of Representatives by December 1 of each year. The
9 report shall include:
10 1. The number of organizations that receive grants;
11 2. The total amount of grant funds distributed;
12 3. An aggregate summary of services provided and victims
13 served;
14 4. An evaluation of the effectiveness of the pilot program; and
15 5. Recommendations for improvement of the pilot program.
16 F. The Office of the Attorney General shall promulgate rules to
17 effectuate the provisions of this act.
18 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY Section 1, Chapter 376, O.S.L.
19 2023 (21 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 748.3), is amended to read as
20 follows:
21 Section 748.3. A. There is hereby created in the State
22 Treasury a revolving fund for the Office of the Attorney General to
23 be designated the “Victims of Human Trafficking and Prevention
24 Revolving Fund”. The fund shall be a continuing fund, not subject
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 1379 Page 6

1 to f iscal year limitations, and shall consist of all monies received
2 from penalties imposed by the courts on convictions of human
3 trafficking violations and funds received from any other source,
4 including legislative appropriations. All monies accruing to the
5 credit of the fund are hereby appropriated and may be budgeted and
6 expended by the Office of the Attorney General for the purposes
7 provided in subsection B of this section. Expenditures from the
8 fund shall be made upon warrants issued by the State Treasurer
9 against claims filed as prescribed by law with the Director of the
10 Office of Management and Enterprise Services for approval and
11 payment.
12 B. The purposes of the fund include, but are not limited to:
13 1. Educating the public about the recruitment, trafficking, and
14 exploitation of persons through human trafficking;
15 2. Assisting in the prevention of recruitment in schools of
16 minors for exploitation;
17 3. Establishing a survivors’ resource center to make
18 information available to survivors of human trafficking about
19 services and resources, including legal services, social services,
20 safe harbors, safe houses, and language services;
21 4. Assisting in the coordination between law enforcement
22 agencies and service providers; and
23 5. Providing information concerning a petition for expungement
24 of a criminal history record resulting from the arrest or filing of
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 1379 Page 7

1 char ges for an offense committed or reported to have been committed
2 while the person was a victim of human trafficking; and
3 6. Providing grants to nonprofit organizations pursuant to
4 Section 1 of this act.
5 SECTION 3. This act shall become effective July 1, 2026.
6 SECTION 4. It being immediately necessary for the preservation
7 of the public peace, health or safety, an emergency is hereby
8 declared to exist, by reason whereof this act shall take effect and
9 be in full force from and after its passage and approval."
10 Passed the House of Representatives the 29th day of April, 2026.
